<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-165-084  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 165 084.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Decisions  March 1989 v21 n3 p34(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big users push for standards. (Technology trends - manufacturingsystems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Francett, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The proliferation of technical workstations brings with it an evengreater need for standards.andP;  Individual workstations make usersmore productive and innovative, but the machines also put up newbarriers to sharing information.andP;  Managers prefer to installmultivendor systems, exacerbating the communications problem, butproviding users with the machines best suited to their needs.andO;Notable users pushing for standards include officials at NorthropCorp's Aircraft Div, McDonnell Douglas Corp's Huntington Beach,CA, facility, the US Department of Defense and General MotorsCorp. A history of the Programmers Hierarchical InteractiveGraphics Standard (PHIGS) shows the difficulty and time involvedin getting a standard.andP;  Work began on PHIGS in 1981 and the finaltext was approved in the fall of 1988.andP;  Standards are not static;they continue to evolve to keep up with technology and user needs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     StandardizationWorkstationsGraphics SoftwareAutomationManufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The PHIGS standard. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>